\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ogemaw County, Michigan|Ogemaw]]\n|5\n|0\n|20,952\n|24\n|0\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ontonagon County, Michigan|Ontonagon]]\n|0\n|0\n|5,795\n|0\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Osceola County, Michigan|Osceola]]\n|6\n|0\n|23,341\n|26\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Oscoda County, Michigan|Oscoda]]\n|4\n|0\n|8,276\n|48\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Otsego County, Michigan|Otsego]]\n|44\n|2\n|24,665\n|176\n|8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa]]\n|82\n|2\n|290,494\n|28\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Presque Isle County, Michigan|Presque Isle]]\n|2\n|0\n|12,738\n|16\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Roscommon County, Michigan|Roscommon]]\n|9\n|0\n|23,884\n|38\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Saginaw County, Michigan|Saginaw]]\n|349\n|20\n|190,800\n|184\n|11\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sanilac County, Michigan|Sanilac]]\n|25\n|2\n|41,182\n|61\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Schoolcraft County, Michigan|Schoolcraft]]\n|3\n|0\n|8,068\n|37\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Shiawassee County, Michigan|Shiawassee]]\n|70\n|2\n|68,192\n|103\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[St. Clair County, Michigan|St. Clair]]\n|232\n|8\n|159,337\n|146\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[St. Joseph County, Michigan|St. Joseph]]\n|23\n|1\n|61,043\n|38\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tuscola County, Michigan|Tuscola]]\n|50\n|10\n|52,516\n|95\n|19\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Van Buren County, Michigan|Van Buren]]\n|26\n|2\n|75,448\n|34\n|3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Washtenaw County, Michigan|Washtenaw]]\n|826\n|25\n|370,963\n|223\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne]]\n|13,002\n|981\n|1,753,893\n|741\n|56\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wexford County, Michigan|Wexford]]\n|7\n|1\n|33,466\n|21\n|3\n|- style=\"background:#bee8ff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Michigan Department of Corrections|MDOC]]{{ref label|Note3|c|c}}\n|486\n|12\n|38,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwjnewsradio.radio.com/articles/news/michigans-prison-population-down-for-fifth-straight-year|title=Michigan's Prison Population Down For Fifth Straight Year|date=December 20, 2019|website=WWJ Newsradio 950}}</ref>\n|1,279\n|32\n|- style=\"background:#bee8ff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Federal Correctional Institution, Milan|FCI Milan]]{{ref label|Note4|d|d}}\n|39\n|0\n|1,600\n|2,438\n|0\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Out-of-State{{ref label|Note5|e|e}}\n|144\n|2\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Unknown\n|76\n|4\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |29,263\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |2,093\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n\n<small>Notes:<br>\n{{Note label|Note1|a|a}}Michigan.gov information is updated daily at 3 p.m., with COVID-19 results included as of 10 a.m..<br>\n{{Note label|Note2|b|b}}Deaths must be reported by health care providers, medical examiners/coroners, and recorded by local health departments in order to be counted.<br>\n{{Note label|Note3|c|c}}[[Michigan Department of Corrections]]<br>\n{{Note label|Note4|d|d}}[[Federal Correctional Institution]]<br>\n{{Note label|Note5|e|e}}Patients are not residents, but are being treated within the state of Michigan.<br>\n{{Note label|Note6|f|f}}Recovery total is only updated on Fridays</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus Coronavirus information] from the State of Michigan\n* [https://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/2020/03/updated-maps-michigan-coronavirus-cases-and-exposure-sites.html Updated maps: Michigan coronavirus cases and exposure sites] from MLive.com\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Michigan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Michigan|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Health in Michigan]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "TomCat4680", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 15\u201321", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Vulcain (watch company)", "text_new": "{{coord|46.16629|6.11211|display=title}}\n{{short description|Swiss luxury watch manufacturer}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Vulcain\n| logo                = Logo_Vulcain_Watches.jpg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| type                = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| industry            = Luxury [[watchmaking]]\n| foundation          = 1858 (Manufacture Ditisheim.)<br />1894 (Vulcain)\n| founder             = [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]]\n| location            = [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Canton of Neuch\u00e2tel]], [[Switzerland]]\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Aldo Magada\n| products            = Watches\n| production          = 3,000 (2018)<ref name=\"Watch Insider\">{{Cite news|url=https://watch-insider.com/economy/figures-figures-figures-estimated-watches-sold-estimated-turnover-major-watch-brands-switzerland-germany/|title=Estimated Watches Sold And Estimated Turnover Of The Major Watch Brands In Switzerland And Germany (Updated 09.06.2013 & 06.08.2013)|date=2013|work=Watch Insider|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en}}</ref>\n| revenue             = \n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = \n| num_employees       = 12\n| parent              = Excellence Holding\n| subsid              = \n| footnotes           = \n| homepage            = {{URL|vulcain.ch}}\n}}\n\n'''Vulcain''' is a [[Swiss watch|Swiss Watchmaker]] that was founded in 1858 by [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]] as ''Manufacture Ditisheim' in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]],'' being rebranded as Vulcain in 1894. In 1947, Vulcain developed the first [[Watch|alarm watch]], the Vulcain Cricket.\n\n== Foundation ==\n\nVulcain was founded in 1858 in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Switzerland]] by the [[Ditisheim]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horlogerie-suisse.com/marques/vulcain|title=Vulcain - Les marques|website=Horlogerie Suisse|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In the family studio, [[Ditisheim]] made [[pocket watch]]es, which he sold under his own name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mb.nawcc.org/threads/vulcain-pocket-watch-any-info-at-all-v-welcome.49122/|title=Vulcain Pocket Watch, Any info at all v. welcome!|website=NAWCC Message Board|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Through to the end of the Century, the watchmaker was called \"''Manufacture Ditisheim\"''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hodkin|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vTG_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA196&lpg=PA196&dq=Manufacture+Ditisheim&source=bl&ots=Enpz8rWZFt&sig=ACfU3U1KmB-lEEI3QjIkIwukBItPAs_cQg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiM0YH5s9noAhWJYMAKHdjUD9sQ6AEwDHoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=Manufacture%20Ditisheim&f=false|title=Collecting Clocks Clock Repairs & Trademarks Index|date=2015-04-20|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-326-25249-6|language=en}}</ref> In [[1894]], watches were first offered under the branding of ''Vulcain,'' with the company now under the leadership of [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim's]] son, Ernest-Albert Ditisheim.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines|first=Reyne|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HhJjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT581&lpg=PT581&dq=vulcain+1894&source=bl&ots=V0O5F8_M3t&sig=ACfU3U0ILDp0qxIN9ZB5ULL6SWewQNTMug&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiz1KuHtNnoAhXai1wKHQVQBNkQ6AEwD3oECBEQKQ#v=onepage&q=vulcain%201894&f=false|title=Vintage Wristwatches|date=2010-03-15|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|language=en}}</ref> In [[1900]], [[Ditisheim]] registered the name 'Vulcain' as a brand name for his [[pocket watch]]es, naming it after the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] god of Fire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monochrome-watches.com/old-school-vulcain-cricket/|title=Old School \u2013 Vulcain Cricket|date=2011-08-17|website=Monochrome Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nUp until [[World War II]], Vulcain solely focused on the production of [[Pocket watch]]es, only turning to wristwatches with the uptake in popularity of wristwatches for the [[military]].\n\n=== The Alarm Watch ===\nIn the early 1940s, Vulcain invented the idea of a [[Mechanical watch|mechanical alarm watch]]. There had been two prior attempts by other watchmakers in the early [[19th century]], but these projects were failures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/17/full-alert-a-history-of-alarm-watches|title=Full Alert: A History of Alarm Watches|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1942, Vulcain had begun production of a prototype alarm [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], later named the 120.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ranfft.de/cgi-bin/bidfun-db.cgi?10&ranfft&&2uswk&Vulcain_120|title=bidfun-db Archive: Watch Movements: Vulcain 120 Cricket|website=www.ranfft.de|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Caliber 120 could sound for above 20 seconds when fully would through the invention of the 'dual barrel'. This system ensured two separate [[Barrel (horology)|barrels]], which contain the wound up springs generating energy for the watch. These barrels separately provided energy for the [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], and for the [[Alarm device|alarm]]; hence ensuring that the watch could sound for significantly longer than prior iterations.\n\nThe development of the volume, developed alongside French [[Physisist]] [[Paul Langevin]] took a further 5 years, when Vulcain patented a double-case design to reverberate the sound further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchuseek.com/the-presidents-watch-history-and-review-of-vulcain-alarm-watch/|title=The Presidents\u2019 Watch \u2013 History and Review of Vulcain Alarm Watch|last=February 15|first=Bhanu Chopra on|last2=2016|date=2016-02-15|website=watchuseek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchcollectinglifestyle.com/home/news-vulcain-cricket-president-edition-france-50-piece-limited-edition|title=News: Vulcain Cricket President 'Edition France'. 50-Piece Limited Edition.|website=WATCH COLLECTING LIFESTYLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The sound of the alarm notably sounded similar to that of a [[Cricket (insect)|cricket]], with the insect serving as its namesake.\n\nThe Cricket, released in 1947, ran off of the final iteration of the Caliber 120, which was 17 -[[Watch jewel|Jewels]], had a near two-day power reserved and beat at 18,000 Beats per hour.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Presidential tradition ==\nVulcain gained brand recognition from the early 1950s for their invention of the [[Watch|alarm watch]] - the Vulcain [[Cricket]], which was presented at a Swiss Watch Fair in [[1947]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fratellowatches.com/tbt-worlds-first-alarm-wrist-watch-vulcain-cricket/|title=#TBT World's first alarm wrist watch Vulcain Cricket|date=2019-06-13|website=Fratello Watches|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onewheee.com/vulcain-cricket-1947-heritage-replica-hands/|title=Vulcain Cricket 1947 Heritage Replica Hands On|date=2017-11-06|website=OneWheee|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.analogshift.com/products/vulcain-cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket|website=Analog/Shift|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, The [[White House Correspondents' Association|White House Press Photographer's Association]] presented [[Harry S. Truman]] with a [[14kt gold|14k gold]] version of the watch on the eve of his leaving presidential office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2016/6/20/the-vulcain-cricket-made-for-men-worn-by-presidents|title=The Vulcain Cricket: Made for Men, Worn by Presidents|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.crownandcaliber.com/vulcain-cricket/|title=The Vulcain Cricket: The Watch of Presidents|last=Crown & Caliber|date=2017-02-17|website=Crown & Caliber Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://historical.ha.com/itm/political/presidential-relics/harry-s-truman-personally-owned-vulcain-cricket-wrist-watch/a/6126-42139.s|title=Harry S Truman: Personally Owned Vulcain Cricket Wrist Watch.... {{!}} Lot #42139|website=Heritage Auctions|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Following from this, nearly every President has been gifted one to commemorate their leaving office.\n\nThe Cricket also served as an adventurers watch, as the brand in [[Le Locle]] had partnered with multiple [[mountaineering]] and [[Maritime history|maritime expeditions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://world.vulcain-watches.ch/en/world/adventure/|title=Adventure: Vulcain|website=world.vulcain-watches.ch|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchtime.com/featured/watch-u-s-presidents-timepieces/|title=First Watch: U.S. Presidents and Their Timepieces|last=Buchanan|first=Written byNorma|date=2020-02-17|website=WatchTime - USA's No.1 Watch Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=07be13b0-79cf-11ea-8fd1-9bc65fb8c932&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxNi0xMi0wOC90cnVtcC10by1nZXQtaW5hdWd1cmFsLXRpbWVwaWVjZS1mcm9tLWFpbGluZy1zd2lzcy13YXRjaG1ha2Vy|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-06/a-mechanical-alarm-watch-that-every-president-owns|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Extended Watch Range ==\nVulcain, introduced the ''Cricket Nautical'' in 1961.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodinkee.com/articles/a-week-on-the-wrist-vulcain-nautical-cricket|title=A Week On The Wrist: The Vulcain Nautical Cricket|last=November 07|first=Blake Buettner|last2=2012|website=HODINKEE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/25/designed-to-go-where-we-at-not-the-vulcain-cricket-nautical|title=Designed to go where we at not: The Vulcain Cricket Nautical|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The watch [[Alarm device|alarm]] was marketed as being audible underwater.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gaillard|first=Aur\u00e9lia|title=Vulcain et sa forge aux xviie et xviiie si\u00e8cles\u00a0: Vulcain d\u00e9senchant\u00e9, Volcan enchant\u00e9 \u2013 d'un imaginaire \u00e0 l'autre|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.pur.30843|work=L'imaginaire du volcan|pages=115\u2013131|publisher=Presses universitaires de Rennes|isbn=978-2-7535-0023-5|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europastar.com/magazine/highlights/1004084736-vulcain-the-cricket-conquers.html|title=Vulcain \u2013 The Cricket conquers|last=Strandberg|first=Keith W.|website=www.europastar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Quartz Crisis ==\n\n[[1961]] the companies [[Revue]], [[Vulcain]], [[Buser]] and [[Ph\u00e9nix]] merged to form the \"Manufactures d'Horlogerie Suisse R\u00e9unis SA\" (MSR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.watchisthis.com/buser-freres-cie-s-a-a-brief-introduction/|title=Buser Fr\u00e8res & Cie S.A. \u2013 A Brief Introduction|website=www.watchisthis.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring the so-called [[quartz crisis]] in the 1980s, Vulcain struggled as the market for high-quality luxury mechanical [[wristwatch]]es collapsed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montredo.com/en-gb/the-quartz-crisis/|title=The Quartz Crisis: The almost-downfall of the mechanical watch|date=2019-07-24|website=Montredo|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The future was seen to belong to cheap [[quartz watch]]es. Vulcain still produced their watches for sister brands within the [[MSR]]{{disambiguation needed|date=April 2020}}, but had a temporary break in manufacture. When the Cricket was produced again under the name of \"[[Revue Thommen]]\", this was done in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swissluxurywatches.ch/product-category/revue-thommen/|title=Revue Thommen Watches At Discount Prices|website=Swiss Luxury Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Restart of the brand Vulcain under the PMH (Production et Marketing Horologer) ==\n\nTowards the end of the [[1990]]<nowiki/>s, Vulcain was sold by MSR. After its bankruptcy at the end of the 1990s, the PMH (Production et marketing Horologer) acquired all rights to the brand and the Vulcain Cricket V10 was introduced in [[2001]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watch-wiki.net/index.php?title=Vulcain_Cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket - Watch Wiki: The Best Watches and Watch Brands|website=www.watch-wiki.net|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThis new beginning was associated with the relocation from [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]] to [[Le Locle]], known for its association with the watch industry.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines, Reyne.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/767501001|title=Vintage Wristwatches.|date=2010|publisher=F+W Media|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|location=Cincinnati|oclc=767501001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/la-chaux-de-fonds-city-of-watchmakers/a-45343653|title=La Chaux-de-Fonds - City of watchmakers {{!}} DW {{!}} 11.09.2018|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2002]], the first new models of the Vulcain were presented, largely based on historical models.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.vulcain-watches.com/ Vulcain (company website)]\n\n[[Category:Watch brands]]\n[[Category:Le Locle]]\n[[Category:La Chaux-de-Fonds]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|46.16629|6.11211|display=title}}\n{{short description|Swiss luxury watch manufacturer}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Vulcain\n| logo                = Logo_Vulcain_Watches.jpg\n| logo_size           = 200px\n| type                = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| industry            = Luxury [[watchmaking]]\n| foundation          = 1858 (Manufacture Ditisheim.)<br />1894 (Vulcain)\n| founder             = [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]]\n| location            = [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Canton of Neuch\u00e2tel]], [[Switzerland]]\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = Bernard Fleury\n| products            = Watches\n| production          = 3,000 (2018)<ref name=\"Watch Insider\">{{Cite news|url=https://watch-insider.com/economy/figures-figures-figures-estimated-watches-sold-estimated-turnover-major-watch-brands-switzerland-germany/|title=Estimated Watches Sold And Estimated Turnover Of The Major Watch Brands In Switzerland And Germany (Updated 09.06.2013 & 06.08.2013)|date=2013|work=Watch Insider|access-date=2020-04-04|language=en}}</ref>\n| revenue             = \n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = \n| num_employees       = 12\n| parent              = Excellence Holding\n| subsid              = \n| footnotes           = \n| homepage            = {{URL|vulcain.ch}}\n}}\n\n'''Vulcain''' is a [[Swiss watch|Swiss Watchmaker]] that was founded in 1858 by [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim]] as ''Manufacture Ditisheim' in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]],'' being rebranded as Vulcain in 1894. In 1947, Vulcain developed the first [[Watch|alarm watch]], the Vulcain Cricket.\n\n== Foundation ==\n\nVulcain was founded in 1858 in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]], [[Switzerland]] by the [[Ditisheim]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horlogerie-suisse.com/marques/vulcain|title=Vulcain - Les marques|website=Horlogerie Suisse|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> In the family studio, [[Ditisheim]] made [[pocket watch]]es, which he sold under his own name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mb.nawcc.org/threads/vulcain-pocket-watch-any-info-at-all-v-welcome.49122/|title=Vulcain Pocket Watch, Any info at all v. welcome!|website=NAWCC Message Board|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Through to the end of the Century, the watchmaker was called \"''Manufacture Ditisheim\"''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hodkin|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vTG_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA196&lpg=PA196&dq=Manufacture+Ditisheim&source=bl&ots=Enpz8rWZFt&sig=ACfU3U1KmB-lEEI3QjIkIwukBItPAs_cQg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiM0YH5s9noAhWJYMAKHdjUD9sQ6AEwDHoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=Manufacture%20Ditisheim&f=false|title=Collecting Clocks Clock Repairs & Trademarks Index|date=2015-04-20|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-326-25249-6|language=en}}</ref> In [[1894]], watches were first offered under the branding of ''Vulcain,'' with the company now under the leadership of [[Ditisheim|Maurice Ditisheim's]] son, Ernest-Albert Ditisheim.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines|first=Reyne|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HhJjDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT581&lpg=PT581&dq=vulcain+1894&source=bl&ots=V0O5F8_M3t&sig=ACfU3U0ILDp0qxIN9ZB5ULL6SWewQNTMug&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiz1KuHtNnoAhXai1wKHQVQBNkQ6AEwD3oECBEQKQ#v=onepage&q=vulcain%201894&f=false|title=Vintage Wristwatches|date=2010-03-15|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|language=en}}</ref> In [[1900]], [[Ditisheim]] registered the name 'Vulcain' as a brand name for his [[pocket watch]]es, naming it after the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] god of Fire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://monochrome-watches.com/old-school-vulcain-cricket/|title=Old School \u2013 Vulcain Cricket|date=2011-08-17|website=Monochrome Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nUp until [[World War II]], Vulcain solely focused on the production of [[Pocket watch]]es, only turning to wristwatches with the uptake in popularity of wristwatches for the [[military]].\n\n=== The Alarm Watch ===\nIn the early 1940s, Vulcain invented the idea of a [[Mechanical watch|mechanical alarm watch]]. There had been two prior attempts by other watchmakers in the early [[19th century]], but these projects were failures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/17/full-alert-a-history-of-alarm-watches|title=Full Alert: A History of Alarm Watches|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1942, Vulcain had begun production of a prototype alarm [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], later named the 120.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ranfft.de/cgi-bin/bidfun-db.cgi?10&ranfft&&2uswk&Vulcain_120|title=bidfun-db Archive: Watch Movements: Vulcain 120 Cricket|website=www.ranfft.de|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Caliber 120 could sound for above 20 seconds when fully would through the invention of the 'dual barrel'. This system ensured two separate [[Barrel (horology)|barrels]], which contain the wound up springs generating energy for the watch. These barrels separately provided energy for the [[Movement (clockwork)|movement]], and for the [[Alarm device|alarm]]; hence ensuring that the watch could sound for significantly longer than prior iterations.\n\nThe development of the volume, developed alongside French [[Physisist]] [[Paul Langevin]] took a further 5 years, when Vulcain patented a double-case design to reverberate the sound further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchuseek.com/the-presidents-watch-history-and-review-of-vulcain-alarm-watch/|title=The Presidents\u2019 Watch \u2013 History and Review of Vulcain Alarm Watch|last=February 15|first=Bhanu Chopra on|last2=2016|date=2016-02-15|website=watchuseek.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchcollectinglifestyle.com/home/news-vulcain-cricket-president-edition-france-50-piece-limited-edition|title=News: Vulcain Cricket President 'Edition France'. 50-Piece Limited Edition.|website=WATCH COLLECTING LIFESTYLE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The sound of the alarm notably sounded similar to that of a [[Cricket (insect)|cricket]], with the insect serving as its namesake.\n\nThe Cricket, released in 1947, ran off of the final iteration of the Caliber 120, which was 17 -[[Watch jewel|Jewels]], had a near two-day power reserved and beat at 18,000 Beats per hour.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Presidential tradition ==\nVulcain gained brand recognition from the early 1950s for their invention of the [[Watch|alarm watch]] - the Vulcain [[Cricket]], which was presented at a Swiss Watch Fair in [[1947]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fratellowatches.com/tbt-worlds-first-alarm-wrist-watch-vulcain-cricket/|title=#TBT World's first alarm wrist watch Vulcain Cricket|date=2019-06-13|website=Fratello Watches|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onewheee.com/vulcain-cricket-1947-heritage-replica-hands/|title=Vulcain Cricket 1947 Heritage Replica Hands On|date=2017-11-06|website=OneWheee|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shop.analogshift.com/products/vulcain-cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket|website=Analog/Shift|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, The [[White House Correspondents' Association|White House Press Photographer's Association]] presented [[Harry S. Truman]] with a [[14kt gold|14k gold]] version of the watch on the eve of his leaving presidential office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2016/6/20/the-vulcain-cricket-made-for-men-worn-by-presidents|title=The Vulcain Cricket: Made for Men, Worn by Presidents|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.crownandcaliber.com/vulcain-cricket/|title=The Vulcain Cricket: The Watch of Presidents|last=Crown & Caliber|date=2017-02-17|website=Crown & Caliber Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://historical.ha.com/itm/political/presidential-relics/harry-s-truman-personally-owned-vulcain-cricket-wrist-watch/a/6126-42139.s|title=Harry S Truman: Personally Owned Vulcain Cricket Wrist Watch.... {{!}} Lot #42139|website=Heritage Auctions|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Following from this, nearly every President has been gifted one to commemorate their leaving office.\n\nThe Cricket also served as an adventurers watch, as the brand in [[Le Locle]] had partnered with multiple [[mountaineering]] and [[Maritime history|maritime expeditions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://world.vulcain-watches.ch/en/world/adventure/|title=Adventure: Vulcain|website=world.vulcain-watches.ch|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchtime.com/featured/watch-u-s-presidents-timepieces/|title=First Watch: U.S. Presidents and Their Timepieces|last=Buchanan|first=Written byNorma|date=2020-02-17|website=WatchTime - USA's No.1 Watch Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=07be13b0-79cf-11ea-8fd1-9bc65fb8c932&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxNi0xMi0wOC90cnVtcC10by1nZXQtaW5hdWd1cmFsLXRpbWVwaWVjZS1mcm9tLWFpbGluZy1zd2lzcy13YXRjaG1ha2Vy|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-06/a-mechanical-alarm-watch-that-every-president-owns|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Extended Watch Range ==\nVulcain, introduced the ''Cricket Nautical'' in 1961.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hodinkee.com/articles/a-week-on-the-wrist-vulcain-nautical-cricket|title=A Week On The Wrist: The Vulcain Nautical Cricket|last=November 07|first=Blake Buettner|last2=2012|website=HODINKEE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timepiecechronicle.com/features/2017/1/25/designed-to-go-where-we-at-not-the-vulcain-cricket-nautical|title=Designed to go where we at not: The Vulcain Cricket Nautical|website=Timepiece Chronicle|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The watch [[Alarm device|alarm]] was marketed as being audible underwater.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gaillard|first=Aur\u00e9lia|title=Vulcain et sa forge aux xviie et xviiie si\u00e8cles\u00a0: Vulcain d\u00e9senchant\u00e9, Volcan enchant\u00e9 \u2013 d'un imaginaire \u00e0 l'autre|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.4000/books.pur.30843|work=L'imaginaire du volcan|pages=115\u2013131|publisher=Presses universitaires de Rennes|isbn=978-2-7535-0023-5|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.europastar.com/magazine/highlights/1004084736-vulcain-the-cricket-conquers.html|title=Vulcain \u2013 The Cricket conquers|last=Strandberg|first=Keith W.|website=www.europastar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== The Quartz Crisis ==\n\n[[1961]] the companies [[Revue]], [[Vulcain]], [[Buser]] and [[Ph\u00e9nix]] merged to form the \"Manufactures d'Horlogerie Suisse R\u00e9unis SA\" (MSR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.watchisthis.com/buser-freres-cie-s-a-a-brief-introduction/|title=Buser Fr\u00e8res & Cie S.A. \u2013 A Brief Introduction|website=www.watchisthis.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nDuring the so-called [[quartz crisis]] in the 1980s, Vulcain struggled as the market for high-quality luxury mechanical [[wristwatch]]es collapsed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montredo.com/en-gb/the-quartz-crisis/|title=The Quartz Crisis: The almost-downfall of the mechanical watch|date=2019-07-24|website=Montredo|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The future was seen to belong to cheap [[quartz watch]]es. Vulcain still produced their watches for sister brands within the [[MSR]]{{disambiguation needed|date=April 2020}}, but had a temporary break in manufacture. When the Cricket was produced again under the name of \"[[Revue Thommen]]\", this was done in [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://swissluxurywatches.ch/product-category/revue-thommen/|title=Revue Thommen Watches At Discount Prices|website=Swiss Luxury Watches|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Restart of the brand Vulcain under the PMH (Production et Marketing Horologer) ==\n\nTowards the end of the [[1990]]<nowiki/>s, Vulcain was sold by MSR. After its bankruptcy at the end of the 1990s, the PMH (Production et marketing Horologer) acquired all rights to the brand and the Vulcain Cricket V10 was introduced in [[2001]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watch-wiki.net/index.php?title=Vulcain_Cricket|title=Vulcain Cricket - Watch Wiki: The Best Watches and Watch Brands|website=www.watch-wiki.net|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nThis new beginning was associated with the relocation from [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]] to [[Le Locle]], known for its association with the watch industry.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haines, Reyne.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/767501001|title=Vintage Wristwatches.|date=2010|publisher=F+W Media|isbn=978-1-4402-1524-7|location=Cincinnati|oclc=767501001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/la-chaux-de-fonds-city-of-watchmakers/a-45343653|title=La Chaux-de-Fonds - City of watchmakers {{!}} DW {{!}} 11.09.2018|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche|website=DW.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2002]], the first new models of the Vulcain were presented, largely based on historical models.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.vulcain-watches.com/ Vulcain (company website)]\n\n[[Category:Watch brands]]\n[[Category:Le Locle]]\n[[Category:La Chaux-de-Fonds]]\n", "name_user": "SerAntoniDeMiloni", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed to show correct CEO", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vulcain_(watch_company)"}
{"title_page": "Pasolini (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pasolini\n| image          = Pasolini-Abel-Ferrara.jpg\n| caption        = Italian theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Abel Ferrara]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Thierry Lounas\n* Conchita Airoldi\n* Joseph Rouschop\n}}\n| writer         = Maurizio Braucci\n| story       = {{Plainlist|\n* Abel Ferrara\n* Nicola Tranquillino\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Willem Dafoe]]\n* [[Ninetto Davoli]]\n* [[Riccardo Scamarcio]]\n* [[Valerio Mastandrea]]\n* [[Adriana Asti]]\n* [[Giada Colagrande]]\n* [[Maria de Medeiros]]\n}}\n| narrator       = [[Luca Lionello]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Stefano Falivene\n| editing        = Fabio Nunziata\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Capricci Films\n* Urania Pictures\n* Tarantula\n* Dublin Films\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* Capricci Films {{small|(France)}}\n* Europictures {{small|(Italy)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|09|04|[[71st Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2014|09|25|Italy|2014|12|31|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 84:11--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/pasolini-film | title=''Pasolini'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=3 August 2015 | accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* France\n* Italy\n* Belgium\n}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Italian\n* French\n}}\n}}\n'''''Pasolini''''' is a 2014 English-language internationally co-produced [[drama film]] directed by [[Abel Ferrara]] and written by Maurizio Braucci about the final days of Italian film director [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]]. It was selected to compete for the [[Golden Lion]] at the [[71st Venice International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Venice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |title=International competition of feature films |accessdate=24 July 2014 |work=Venice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006083927/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |archivedate=6 October 2014  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/venice-film-festival-lineup-2014-movie-list/ |title=Venice Film Festival Lineup Announced |accessdate=24 July 2014 |work=Deadline}}</ref> It was also screened in the Special Presentations section of the [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Indiewire\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/tiff-toronto-intl-film-festival-gala-special-presentations-1201266480/ |title=Toronto Film Festival Lineup |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=Variety}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n[[Pier Paolo Pasolini]] ([[Willem Dafoe]]) is fifty-three, and lives in the rowdy [[Rome]] of the 1970s. He has just finished shooting his latest film ''[[Sal\u00f2, or the 120 Days of Sodom]]'', a film that has shocked both critics and audiences. Pasolini is increasingly opposed by the people, critics and politicians, both for his [[homosexuality]], and because he is considered impulsive and scandalous in showing his reality to the public. Pasolini is going to shoot a new film (which was never made), in which he cast [[Ninetto Davoli]] as the famous Italian actor [[Eduardo De Filippo]] and [[Riccardo Scamarcio]] as the young De Fillipo - with whom he has a special relationship. While Pasolini is working on the film, his mother ([[Adriana Asti]]) and his sister try to dissuade him from the project, because it would be too wild and visionary for the Italian public to accept.\n\nPasolini continues with his work, missing many interviews with journalists. He begins a relationship with a boy from the suburbs of Rome, Pino Pelosi, and takes him to a restaurant in the seaside village of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]]. Pasolini wants to be with him in a loving relationship, but the boy gets mad at him, attacking him and some other companions. Pasolini is later beaten up, and then run over with his own car. In the days following, the press says Pasolini's murder was politically motivated by the police and those whom the poet had always loved and immortalized in his works.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Willem Dafoe]] as [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]]\n* [[Ninetto Davoli]] as [[Eduardo De Filippo]]\n* [[Riccardo Scamarcio]] as [[Ninetto Davoli]]\n* [[Valerio Mastandrea]] as Domenico \"Nico\" Naldini\n* [[Adriana Asti]] as Susanna Pasolini\n* [[Giada Colagrande]] as Graziella Chiarcossi\n* [[Maria de Medeiros]] as [[Laura Betti]]\n* Francesco Siciliano as [[Furio Colombo]]\n* [[Luca Lionello]] as narrator\n\n==Production==\nAccording to Ferrara, his plans to make a film about Pasolini have gone far back as the 1990s. Originally, the project was not meant to have been an actual biopic of Pasolini's life.  Instead, it was to have starred [[Zo\u00eb Tamerlis Lund]] as \"a female director living the life that Pasolini lived.\" However, Lund's death prevented this idea.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vestby|first=Ethan|title=Abel Ferrara On Artistic Freedom, Collaboration, \u2018Ms. 45,\u2019 Pier Paolo Pasolini & More|date=9 December 2013|url=http://thefilmstage.com/features/abel-ferrara-on-artistic-freedom-collaboration-ms-45-pier-paolo-pasolini-more/|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn the review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 78% approval rating, based on 51 reviews, with a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.89/10. The website's consensus reads, \"''Pasolini'' may frustrate viewers seeking a straightforward biopic, but director Abel Ferrara's unconventional approach is well-matched by Willem Dafoe's performance.\"<ref>{{rottentomatoes|pasolini_2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 71 out of 100, based on 18 critics.<ref>{{metacritic film|pasolini}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3125652|Pasolini}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|pasolini_2014|Pasolini}}\n* {{metacritic film|pasolini|Pasolini}}\n* {{mojo title|pasolini}}\n\n{{Abel Ferrara}}\n{{Pier Paolo Pasolini}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pasolini}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Belgian films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Belgian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:French biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:French LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Italian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Abel Ferrara]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2014 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pasolini\n| image          = Pasolini-Abel-Ferrara.jpg\n| caption        = Italian theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Abel Ferrara]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Thierry Lounas\n* Conchita Airoldi\n* Joseph Rouschop\n}}\n| writer         = Maurizio Braucci\n| story       = {{Plainlist|\n* Abel Ferrara\n* Nicola Tranquillino\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Willem Dafoe]]\n* [[Ninetto Davoli]]\n* [[Riccardo Scamarcio]]\n* [[Valerio Mastandrea]]\n* [[Adriana Asti]]\n* [[Giada Colagrande]]\n* [[Maria de Medeiros]]\n}}\n| narrator       = [[Luca Lionello]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Stefano Falivene\n| editing        = Fabio Nunziata\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Capricci Films\n* Urania Pictures\n* Tarantula\n* Dublin Films\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* Capricci Films {{small|(France)}}\n* Europictures {{small|(Italy)}}\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|09|04|[[71st Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2014|09|25|Italy|2014|12|31|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 84 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 84:11--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/pasolini-film | title=''Pasolini'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=3 August 2015 | accessdate=3 August 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* France\n* Italy\n* Belgium\n}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* Italian\n* French\n}}\n}}\n'''''Pasolini''''' is a 2014 English-language internationally co-produced [[drama film]] directed by [[Abel Ferrara]] and written by Maurizio Braucci about the final days of Italian film director [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]]. It was selected to compete for the [[Golden Lion]] at the [[71st Venice International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Venice\">{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |title=International competition of feature films |accessdate=24 July 2014 |work=Venice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006083927/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |archivedate=6 October 2014  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/venice-film-festival-lineup-2014-movie-list/ |title=Venice Film Festival Lineup Announced |accessdate=24 July 2014 |work=Deadline}}</ref> It was also screened in the Special Presentations section of the [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Indiewire\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/tiff-toronto-intl-film-festival-gala-special-presentations-1201266480/ |title=Toronto Film Festival Lineup |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=Variety}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n[[Pier Paolo Pasolini]] ([[Willem Dafoe]]) is fifty-three, and lives in the rowdy [[Rome]] of the 1970s. He has just finished shooting his latest film ''[[Sal\u00f2, or the 120 Days of Sodom]]'', a film that has shocked both critics and audiences. Pasolini is increasingly opposed by the people, critics and politicians, both for his [[homosexuality]], and because he is considered impulsive and scandalous in showing his reality to the public. Pasolini is going to shoot a new film (which was never made), in which he cast [[Ninetto Davoli]] as the famous Italian actor [[Eduardo De Filippo]] and [[Riccardo Scamarcio]] as the young De Fillipo - with whom he has a special relationship. While Pasolini is working on the film, his mother ([[Adriana Asti]]) and his sister try to dissuade him from the project, because it would be too wild and visionary for the Italian public to accept.\n\nPasolini continues with his work, missing many interviews with journalists. He begins a relationship with a boy from the suburbs of Rome, Pino Pelosi, and takes him to a restaurant in the seaside village of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]]. Pasolini wants to be with him in a loving relationship, but the boy gets mad at him, attacking him and some other companions. Pasolini is later beaten up, and then run over with his own car. In the days following, the press says Pasolini's murder was politically motivated by the police and those whom the poet had always loved and immortalized in his works.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Willem Dafoe]] as [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]]\n* [[Ninetto Davoli]] as [[Eduardo De Filippo]]\n* [[Riccardo Scamarcio]] as [[Ninetto Davoli]]\n* [[Valerio Mastandrea]] as Domenico \"Nico\" Naldini\n* [[Adriana Asti]] as Susanna Pasolini\n* [[Giada Colagrande]] as Graziella Chiarcossi\n* [[Maria de Medeiros]] as [[Laura Betti]]\n* Francesco Siciliano as [[Furio Colombo]]\n* [[Luca Lionello]] as narrator\n\n==Production==\nAccording to Ferrara, his plans to make a film about Pasolini have gone far back as the 1990s. Originally, the project was not meant to have been an actual biopic of Pasolini's life.  Instead, it was to have starred [[Zo\u00eb Tamerlis Lund]] as \"a female director living the life that Pasolini lived.\" However, Lund's death prevented this idea.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vestby|first=Ethan|title=Abel Ferrara On Artistic Freedom, Collaboration, \u2018Ms. 45,\u2019 Pier Paolo Pasolini & More|date=9 December 2013|url=http://thefilmstage.com/features/abel-ferrara-on-artistic-freedom-collaboration-ms-45-pier-paolo-pasolini-more/|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn the review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a 78% approval rating, based on 51 reviews, with a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 6.89/10. The website's consensus reads, \"''Pasolini'' may frustrate viewers seeking a straightforward biopic, but director Abel Ferrara's unconventional approach is well-matched by Willem Dafoe's performance.\"<ref>{{rottentomatoes|pasolini_2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 71 out of 100, based on 18 critics.<ref>{{metacritic film|pasolini}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3125652|Pasolini}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|pasolini_2014|Pasolini}}\n* {{metacritic film|pasolini|Pasolini}}\n* {{mojo title|pasolini}}\n\n{{Abel Ferrara}}\n{{Pier Paolo Pasolini}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pasolini}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Belgian films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Belgian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Belgian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:French biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:French LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Italian biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:Films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Abel Ferrara]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/